 Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Boydell was born about 1155, in England, United Kingdom as the son of Helto Marmion de Bois d'Elle and Idonea FitzWilliam. He had at least 1 daughter with Bowes. He died about 1217, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 64."},"et":{"Abt 1155–Abt 1217":"umbes 1155–umbes 1217","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1155–1217":"1155–1217","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1180–1257":"1180–1257","1182–1227":"1182–1227","–1180":"–1180","1128–1180":"1128–1180","1217":"1217","1128":"1128","1227":"1227","1257":"1257","Abt 1155":"umbes 1155","1155":"1155","1150":"1150","Aft 1180":"pärast 1180","1182":"1182","Bef 1180":"enne 1180","1180":"1180","Abt 1217":"umbes 1217","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1155–Abt 1217":"noin 1155–noin 1217","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1155–1217":"1155–1217","1155–Female":"1155–Kuollut","1180–1257":"1180–1257","1182–1227":"1182–1227","–1180":"–1180","1128–1180":"1128–1180","1217":"1217","1128":"1128","1227":"1227","1257":"1257","Abt 1155":"noin 1155","1155":"1155","1150":"1150","Aft 1180":"1180 jälkeen","1182":"1182","Bef 1180":"ennen vuotta 1180","1180":"1180","Abt 1217":"noin 1217","Cheshire, England":"Cheshi